Loading and preprocessing the data

Show any code that is needed to

1. Load the data (i.e. read.csv())

Plese, note that activity.csv should be extracted to working directory.

activity <- read.csv("activity.csv", colClasses = list("numeric", "Date", "numeric"))

2. Process/transform the data (if necessary) into a format suitable for your analysis

2.1. What is mean total number of steps taken per day?

For this part of the assignment, you can ignore the missing values in the dataset.

na <- is.na(activity$steps)
  • Calculate the total number of steps taken per day
steps_per_day <- aggregate(activity$steps[!na], list(activity$date[!na]), sum)
colnames(steps_per_day) <- c("date", "steps")
  • Make a histogram of the total number of steps taken each day
h <- hist(steps_per_day$steps, main = "Steps per day Histogram", xlab = "steps", 
    ylab = "days", labels = TRUE, ylim = range(1:30))

Calculate and report the mean and median of the total number of steps taken per day

mean_steps_per_day <- mean(steps_per_day$steps)
median_steps_per_day <- median(steps_per_day$steps)
plot(steps_per_day, type = "l", xlab = "date", ylab = "steps", main = "Steps per day", 
    col = "blue")
abline(h = median_steps_per_day, col = "black", lty = 1)
abline(h = mean_steps_per_day, col = "orange", lty = 2)

The mean of the total number of steps taken per day is 10766.1886792, and the median is 10765.

2.2. What is the average daily activity pattern?

  • Make a time series plot (i.e. type = “l”) of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all days (y-axis)
avg_steps_per_interval <- aggregate(activity$steps[!na], list(activity$interval[!na]), 
    mean)
colnames(avg_steps_per_interval) <- c("interval", "steps")
plot(avg_steps_per_interval, type = "l", main = "Steps per interval", col = "blue")

  • Which 5-minute interval, on average across all the days in the dataset, contains the maximum number of steps?
max_steps <- max(avg_steps_per_interval$steps)
interval <- avg_steps_per_interval[which(avg_steps_per_interval$steps == max_steps), 
    ]$interval

The interval 835 has the maximum average steps (206).

2.2. Imputing missing values

  • Calculate and report the total number of missing values in the dataset (i.e. the total number of rows with NAs)
missing_values <- sum(is.na(activity$steps))

There are a total of 2304 missing values.

  • Devise a strategy for filling in all of the missing values in the dataset. The strategy does not need to be sophisticated. For example, you could use the mean/median for that day, or the mean for that 5-minute interval, etc.
fill_value <- function(missing_interval) {
    # returns the average steps for the given interval.  avg_steps_per_interval
    # was calculated in 'daily_pattern' chunk
    value <- round(filter(avg_steps_per_interval, interval == missing_interval)$steps)
}
  • Create a new dataset that is equal to the original dataset but with the missing data filled in.
new_activity <- activity
# na mask was calculated in 'na_mask' chunk at the beginning of the file
new_activity[na, ]$steps <- sapply(new_activity[na, ]$interval, fill_value)
  • Make a histogram of the total number of steps taken each day and Calculate and report the mean and median total number of steps taken per day. Do these values differ from the estimates from the first part of the assignment? What is the impact of imputing missing data on the estimates of the total daily number of steps?
new_steps_per_day <- aggregate(new_activity$steps, list(new_activity$date), 
    sum)
colnames(new_steps_per_day) <- c("date", "steps")
new_h <- hist(new_steps_per_day$steps, main = "NEW Steps per day Histogram", 
    xlab = "steps", ylab = "days", labels = TRUE, ylim = range(1:40))

new_mean_steps_per_day <- mean(new_steps_per_day$steps)
new_median_steps_per_day <- median(new_steps_per_day$steps)

The new values for the mean (10765.6393443) and median (10762) of the total number of steps are slightly lower to previous values, 10766.1886792 and 10765 respectively.

It can be observed that the counter of days in the range from 10000 to 15000 steps per day has been increased in 8 days, from 28 to 36, as result of filling the missing values and the resulting the increased steps per day.

2.3. Are there differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends?

  • For this part the weekdays() function may be of some help here. Use the dataset with the filled-in missing values for this part.

  • Create a new factor variable in the dataset with two levels – “weekday” and “weekend” indicating whether a given date is a weekday or weekend day.

new_activity <- mutate(new_activity, weekend = (weekdays(date) == "Saturday" | 
    weekdays(date) == "Sunday"))
  • Make a panel plot containing a time series plot (i.e. type = “l”) of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all weekday days or weekend days (y-axis). See the README file in the GitHub repository to see an example of what this plot should look like using simulated data.
library(lattice)
avg_steps_week_intervals <- aggregate(new_activity$steps, c(list(new_activity$interval), 
    list(new_activity$weekend)), mean)
colnames(avg_steps_week_intervals) <- c("interval", "day_type", "steps")
avg_steps_week_intervals$day_type <- c("Weekend", "Weekday")[avg_steps_week_intervals$day_type + 
    1]
xyplot(avg_steps_week_intervals$steps ~ avg_steps_week_intervals$interval | 
    avg_steps_week_intervals$day_type, type = "l", main = "Panel Plot", xlab = "interval", 
    ylab = "steps", layout = c(1, 3))
